I don't yet know where I stand on the stop and frisk situation.
But I wonder.. Should we not use statistics when making these decisions?

If one particular group, area, or demographic are statisticly more likely to commit a crime, then shouldn't we put more effort towards mitigating crime in those groups/areas/demographics?

Surely, our main efforts should be in tackling why the statistics are as they are. I imagine this can be done with education and economic policies. But while the data shows a particular statistic, I don't see it to be racist at all the implement those mitigation.

Like anything of importance, there's no simple solution. But I feel it's dangerous to start labeling data as racist.

I'll be honest, Media killed a lot of drive to see the movie, as well as being obviously tied to the suicide squad/Snyderverse look. It seems they are ashamed of the comic book characters while at the same time trying to market that they have comic book characters. The characters where NOT like their comic book counter parts (Harley was the closest but I think there was some writing issues that could have been solved by tweaking the script to make it less of an origin story of them meeting meet up.) Nor did they behave like the comic characters. While not the hugest deal breaker... With Dc's track record, and LOADS of media saying the film tackles Misogyny (I go to movies to escape having someone preach at me and tell me how to live my life), that its not for men, one literal Headline that said "Men you aren't needed for the Harley Quinn movie we've got the women and gays", it turned me off the film. Now too be CLEAR, I love the comic (And cartoon) character of Harley, her run in the toons and comics with Poison Ivy have been great fun, and some have even tackled her falling out of the hero/villain game and trying to go straight and how her past harmed her chance at a normal life. I think they could have done far better focusing on her falling "out" of the game and trying to more normalize, and the world resisting due to her connection too the joker. Birds of prey could have been far closer to their comic book counter parts and shown as a VERY skilled team of bad ass female crime fighters. I think an R rating would have worked well, it lets it sell that the bad guy is very bad and that the "good" gals aren't like A list heroes who do NOT kill. Again, I think that the character and DC universe has opportunity and chances too win in fans... But you can't PREACH at the audience, lecture them, or make any part of the general audience feel alienated or like its "Not for them". When you do a business you have to market to everyone to get the most sales possible.


As for Bloomberg? I wouldn't trust anyone that rich in any office of power. He has worked to ensure his own media will not cover any negative press. I'd rather see some Joe or Jane blow from the center of the states take on the job. We need representation from the common people who have felt the impact of these policies.

snippet.textDisplay: For me the biggest reason I didn't see the movie was because it had no build up. The whole point of birds of prey is to show how Harley Quinn grew as a person after being mentally and physically scarred for years by the joker. But we never got that feeling with suicide squad where the joker went out of his way to not only save her but to show how much he loves and needs her, for god sake the last scene in the movie was him saving her. But after one movie you want people to care about a break up from them? That is not reasonable they needed to make a whole movie about the two show how they grew and then show the fall to get people invested. Also, this film follows the same error as suicide squad, with putting five amazing characters into a movie and hoping to give a backstory to them. They have Huntress, Black Canary, Cassandra Cain, Renee Montoya, Black Mask You can't get people invested in all these characters in just one movie, this is like if marvel never took the time to make personal movies for each of their main characters and just made end game as the first movie. It just turns into a movie of trying to understand who these people are and caring about a main plot surrounded around these people who I don't care about because I don't know them. This movie just seems like it was created for people who already read Harley Quinn's comics and Birds of Pray comics because if you haven't you'd miss out on so much context surrounding the story, you can't just shove all these amazing characters into one movie and hope the audience would care about most of them this happened with suicide squad they should have learned from this. Its just trouble decision-making on their part.
